content.text: This is a HE WSI of a CRC case, consisting of lymph nodes or primary tumor section. What is your initial impression of this image?

The thumbnail displays multiple tissue sections. There are approximately 8-9 discrete pieces of tissue, most of which are ovoid with a dense, basophilic (purple) appearance, consistent with lymph nodes. Some fragments are more irregular and contain eosinophilic (pink) areas, which could be surrounding fat, connective tissue, or part of the primary tumor. The overall impression is that this slide is for lymph node staging in a colorectal cancer case.
Are there any places you want to look into further? Give me reasons why you want to look into each region.

I would zoom into this area as part of a systematic examination of every lymph node on the slide. This particular node (the second from the bottom on the left) appears abnormal even at low magnification. Its normal architecture is effaced, and it is replaced by a uniform, dense, dark purple cell population. This raises suspicion for pathology, which could be metastatic carcinoma or a lymphoma. A high-power view is necessary to characterize the cells and determine the nature of the infiltrate. I want to zoom into [coordinates not found]. As a pathologist evaluating a cancer case, every lymph node must be meticulously examined for metastasis. The green box is placed on the lowermost lymph node on the left side of the slide. I would zoom into this area as part of a systematic review of all submitted lymph nodes. The purpose is to assess the lymph node architecture at high magnification, specifically looking for atypical cells, glandular structures, or other evidence of metastatic carcinoma, typically starting in the subcapsular sinus and then moving into the parenchyma. I want to zoom into [coordinates not found]. I would zoom into this area because the green box is located at the periphery of the largest lymph node in the upper left quadrant, specifically at the interface between the lymphoid tissue and the surrounding perinodal fat. Metastatic cancer cells typically travel to lymph nodes via afferent lymphatics and first colonize the subcapsular sinus, which is located just under the capsule at the edge of the node. Therefore, this is a critical and high-yield area to scrutinize for the earliest signs of metastasis and to assess for extracapsular extension. I want to zoom into [coordinates not found]. As a pathologist, my process involves a systematic review of every lymph node on the slide. The green box is located on the second lymph node from the top on the left side. I have zoomed into the periphery of this lymph node because metastatic tumor cells often first arrive and implant in the subcapsular sinus. Examining the edge of the node is therefore crucial for detecting early metastatic deposits, even micrometastases. I want to zoom into [coordinates not found]. The zoom target is the largest and most suspicious-looking lymph node on the slide (the first large node from the left). This node appears to be completely replaced by tumor. I am zooming into the periphery of this node to assess the interface between the tumor infiltrate and the surrounding perinodal soft tissue. The primary goal is to determine if there is extranodal extension (ENE), which means the tumor has breached the lymph node capsule and invaded the surrounding fat. ENE is a critical prognostic factor and is important for accurate staging. I want to zoom into [coordinates not found]. I am zooming into this area as part of a systematic review of all the tissue fragments on the slide. This particular fragment, the second from the top left, appears to be a lymph node. From low power, its architecture looks effaced by a dense, monotonous blue cell population, which is highly suspicious for metastatic carcinoma. I am zooming in to confirm the presence of atypical cells and to assess the interface between the lymph node and the surrounding perinodal fat tissue to check for extranodal extension, which is a critical prognostic factor. I want to zoom into [coordinates not found]. As a pathologist, the primary task is to examine every lymph node for evidence of metastasis. The green box highlights one of the potential lymph nodes for closer inspection. This is part of a systematic review of all tissue on the slide. This particular node, located centrally, shows a dense, solid, and uniformly basophilic appearance, which warrants high-power examination to determine the nature of the cellular population and to search for atypical cells that would indicate metastatic cancer. I want to zoom into [coordinates not found]. I am zooming into this area because it clearly represents one of the lymph nodes that needs to be evaluated for metastasis. As part of a thorough examination, every piece of tissue that could be a lymph node must be assessed at higher magnification. This particular node is located in the lower-central part of the slide. The purpose of zooming in is to examine its architecture and cellular composition to determine if it is a benign (reactive) node or if it contains malignant cells. I want to zoom into [coordinates not found]. I am zooming into this area because it is located at the periphery of a lymph node (the fourth fragment from the left in the top row). The periphery, specifically the subcapsular sinus, is the most common initial site for metastatic deposits. Furthermore, there appears to be some discoloration (which turns out to be ink) at the very edge, and it's important to evaluate the relationship of the lymph node tissue to this inked margin, as it could represent a surgical resection margin or a marked surface. I want to zoom into [coordinates not found]. I am zooming into this area, which is located on the third tissue fragment from the top right, because it represents the interface between the lymph node parenchyma and the surrounding perinodal tissue. At low power, there appears to be an irregular border between the dense purple lymphoid tissue and the lighter pink tissue. This interface is a critical area to examine for evidence of metastasis. Pathologists meticulously scan the subcapsular sinus and the perinodal fat for any atypical cell clusters, as this is a common site for initial metastatic deposits and for assessing extranodal extension. I want to zoom into [coordinates not found]. As a pathologist, my protocol is to examine every lymph node submitted for evaluation. The green box is placed on one of the potential lymph nodes (the third one from the left in the bottom row). I am zooming into this specific area to begin my high-magnification assessment of this node. The goal is to carefully scan the entire node, paying close attention to the subcapsular sinus and the parenchyma, to search for any atypical epithelial cells, glandular formations, or architectural effacement that would indicate metastatic adenocarcinoma. I want to zoom into [coordinates not found]. As a pathologist, I would systematically review each piece of tissue identified as a potential lymph node. The area indicated by the green box is the 3rd lymph node from the right on the bottom row. I would zoom into this specific area to assess its architecture and cellular composition, specifically looking for nests of atypical epithelial cells (metastatic carcinoma) that would disrupt the normal lymphoid structure. The periphery of the node, adjacent to the fat, is a critical area to examine as the subcapsular sinus is often the first site of metastasis. I want to zoom into [coordinates not found]. The zoomed-in area is located within a fragment on the far right that appears to be predominantly fibro-adipose (fatty) tissue rather than a well-defined lymph node. In colorectal cancer staging, it is crucial to meticulously examine the pericolic/perirectal fat for extranodal tumor deposits (also known as satellite nodules) and lymphovascular invasion (LVI). These findings are prognostically significant and can affect the final pN stage. The pathologist is likely scanning this fatty tissue to search for these small, potentially inconspicuous, foci of metastasis that may exist separate from the main lymph nodes. I want to zoom into [coordinates not found]. As a pathologist, my goal is to examine every piece of tissue submitted as a lymph node to check for metastatic cancer. The area indicated by the green box is on one of the smaller tissue fragments on the lower right. I would zoom into this specific area because it shows an irregular interface between the dense purple lymphoid tissue and the pinker, less cellular surrounding tissue. This interface, particularly the subcapsular sinus region, is a common site for initial metastatic deposits. The slightly disorganized and more eosinophilic appearance in that region is suspicious and requires high-magnification assessment to rule out or confirm the presence of tumor cells. I want to zoom into [coordinates not found].
This is ROI 1 and its 40x cyto pattern. What do you observe when you zoom in?

In the zoomed-in area, the normal lymph node architecture is completely effaced by a diffuse and monotonous sheet of small, mature-appearing lymphocytes. These cells have scant cytoplasm, round nuclei, and condensed chromatin. I do not see the glandular structures or clusters of atypical epithelial cells that would be characteristic of metastatic colorectal adenocarcinoma. My impression is that this lymph node is involved by a low-grade B-cell lymphoproliferative disorder, such as Chronic Lymphocytic Leukemia/Small Lymphocytic Lymphoma (CLL/SLL). This would be considered a 'positive' node, but not with metastatic carcinoma, representing a second, synchronous malignancy or a pre-existing condition.
This is ROI 2 and its 40x cyto pattern. What do you observe when you zoom in?

In this high-magnification view, I see a dense and monotonous population of lymphocytes, which are small, round, and dark-staining cells. The normal architecture of the lymph node appears to be preserved. I do not see any atypical epithelial cells, glandular formations, or nests of tumor cells that would indicate metastasis. The tissue appears to be a benign, possibly reactive, lymph node. My impression for this specific field of view is that it is negative for malignancy.
This is ROI 3 and its 40x cyto pattern. What do you observe when you zoom in?

The zoomed-in image shows the junction between the cortex of a lymph node (dense, dark purple lymphoid tissue at the bottom) and the surrounding perinodal adipose tissue (pink connective tissue and large, clear fat cells at the top). The border between the lymph node and fat is well-defined, although there are some lymphocytes infiltrating into the adjacent fat. I do not see any definite nests of atypical epithelial cells, malignant glandular structures, or pools of mucin that would indicate metastatic adenocarcinoma. My impression of this specific high-power field is that it shows a reactive lymph node adjacent to fat, with no evidence of malignancy. The lymph node appears negative in this view.
This is ROI 4 and its 40x cyto pattern. What do you observe when you zoom in?

In this zoomed-in view, I see a dense and uniform population of small, round cells with dark nuclei and minimal cytoplasm, which are characteristic of lymphocytes. The architecture is consistent with that of a lymph node, with some adjacent adipose tissue. There are no atypical cell clusters, glandular formations, or large pleomorphic cells to suggest metastatic carcinoma. My impression of this area is that it represents a benign (reactive) lymph node, and there is no evidence of malignancy here. The dark streak across the image is a processing artifact, likely a fold in the tissue section.
This is ROI 5 and its 40x cyto pattern. What do you observe when you zoom in?

In this high-power view, the top two-thirds of the image show a dense, solid sheet of malignant cells with high nuclear-to-cytoplasmic ratios, hyperchromatic nuclei, and scant cytoplasm, consistent with metastatic carcinoma (likely from a colorectal primary). The bottom third of the image shows perinodal soft tissue containing blood vessels and fibrous tissue. The sheet of tumor cells extends down to and infiltrates into this perinodal tissue, clearly breaching the lymph node capsule. My impression is a positive lymph node with definite extranodal extension (ENE).
This is ROI 6 and its 40x cyto pattern. What do you observe when you zoom in?

In this high-power view, I see that the normal lymph node architecture is completely replaced by sheets of atypical cells. These cells have large, hyperchromatic (darkly stained), and pleomorphic nuclei with scant cytoplasm, consistent with metastatic adenocarcinoma. At the bottom of the image, there is clear evidence of tumor cells infiltrating beyond the lymph node capsule into the surrounding adipose tissue (the large, clear, round spaces). This finding is known as extranodal extension. My impression is a positive lymph node, completely effaced by metastatic adenocarcinoma, with extranodal extension.
This is ROI 7 and its 40x cyto pattern. What do you observe when you zoom in?

The zoomed-in area reveals a dense, monotonous sheet of lymphoid cells, which effaces the normal lymph node architecture. The cells are predominantly small to medium-sized lymphocytes with dark nuclei. In the upper left, there is perinodal adipose tissue and some blue ink, which is used for marking tissue margins. Within this specific field of view, there are no definite malignant epithelial cells, glandular formations, or tumor nests characteristic of metastatic colorectal adenocarcinoma. My impression is that this portion of the lymph node is either showing a very florid reactive process or is involved by a lymphoproliferative disorder. However, given the clinical context of colorectal cancer, the possibility of the node being completely replaced by a poorly differentiated carcinoma that mimics lymphoma cannot be excluded without examining the entire node and potentially performing immunohistochemical stains (e.g., for cytokeratin).
This is ROI 8 and its 40x cyto pattern. What do you observe when you zoom in?

In the zoomed-in view, I see a lymph node embedded in fibro-adipose tissue. The architecture of the lymph node is preserved. It displays multiple, well-defined lymphoid follicles, some with prominent germinal centers. This pattern is known as follicular hyperplasia, which is a benign reactive change. The cellular population consists of small, mature-appearing lymphocytes. I do not see any atypical cells, abnormal glands, or clusters of malignant cells to suggest metastasis. My impression is that this is a benign, reactive lymph node, negative for malignancy.
This is ROI 9 and its 40x cyto pattern. What do you observe when you zoom in?

In this high-magnification view, I see the edge of a lymph node, composed of a dense sheet of small, dark, round lymphocytes. This lymphoid tissue is directly adjacent to surrounding fibroadipose tissue. A prominent feature is the bright green material at the tissue edge, which is surgical ink. The lymphoid parenchyma extends directly to this inked surface, indicating that the lymph node was likely transected or that this represents the inked outer capsule. I do not see any definitive metastatic tumor cells (e.g., atypical glands or malignant cell clusters) in this specific field. My impression is of a benign lymph node fragment with an inked surface.
This is ROI 10 and its 40x cyto pattern. What do you observe when you zoom in?

In this high-magnification view, I can clearly distinguish two tissue types. On the right and bottom, there is dense lymphoid tissue composed of a monotonous population of small, dark lymphocytes. On the left and top, there is perinodal soft tissue, containing fat cells (adipocytes), blood vessels, and fibrous stroma. The key finding is the infiltration of the lymph node parenchyma by cords and sheets of atypical cells that are not native to the lymph node. These cells are larger than the surrounding lymphocytes, have more eosinophilic cytoplasm, and irregular nuclei. This is a classic presentation of metastatic carcinoma within a lymph node. The irregular, infiltrative border between the tumor and the lymphoid tissue confirms that this is a positive (metastatic) lymph node.
This is ROI 11 and its 40x cyto pattern. What do you observe when you zoom in?

In this zoomed-in area, I see a section of a lymph node adjacent to perinodal adipose tissue (fat cells on the left). The lymph node parenchyma is composed of a dense, monotonous population of small, round, dark-staining cells, which are characteristic of lymphocytes. The normal architecture of the lymph node, including follicular structures and interfollicular areas, appears to be preserved. I do not see any definite clusters of atypical cells, abnormal glands, or extensive necrosis that would be suspicious for metastasis in this particular field of view. My impression is that this part of the lymph node is reactive or benign, but I would need to scan the entire tissue section to definitively rule out the presence of a micrometastasis elsewhere in the node.
This is ROI 12 and its 40x cyto pattern. What do you observe when you zoom in?

The zoomed-in view shows a portion of a lymph node adjacent to perinodal adipose tissue (fat). The lymphoid tissue appears well-preserved, with recognizable structures such as lymphoid follicles, some with germinal centers. The cells are predominantly small, mature lymphocytes. I do not see any definite clusters of atypical, large epithelial cells or glandular structures to suggest metastatic adenocarcinoma. My impression is that this is a benign, reactive lymph node, negative for metastasis.
This is ROI 13 and its 40x cyto pattern. What do you observe when you zoom in?

The zoomed-in image shows mature adipose tissue, characterized by large, clear fat cells, interspersed with pink fibrous connective tissue. Several small to medium-sized blood vessels are present, some of which are thick-walled arterioles. At the right and bottom edges of the image, there are scattered aggregates of small, dark, round cells, which are lymphocytes. My impression is that this is a section of perinodal fibro-adipose tissue with a mild, chronic inflammatory infiltrate. In this specific field, there is no evidence of a tumor deposit or lymphovascular invasion. The pathologist would continue to examine the rest of this tissue fragment and others like it.
This is ROI 14 and its 40x cyto pattern. What do you observe when you zoom in?

In this zoomed-in view, I see residual normal lymphoid tissue, which consists of a dense population of small, dark lymphocytes. However, this lymphoid tissue is being infiltrated and partially replaced by clusters and irregular glands of malignant cells. These malignant cells are much larger than the lymphocytes, have more abundant eosinophilic (pink) cytoplasm, and large, pleomorphic, hyperchromatic nuclei. This morphology is characteristic of metastatic adenocarcinoma. My impression is that this is a positive lymph node, confirming the presence of metastasis from the colorectal primary tumor.
